neighborhood_overview: Islington is a wonderfully eclectic blend of cool and established, young and old, long-time residents and newcomers. You can look at the AIRBNB neighbourhood guide for more details. Our flat is on a quiet tree-lined residential street just off Newington Green (North Islington). It's fairly central/urban, but the street is also very friendly - we know most of our neighbours.  Newington Green itself is a great mix of gentrified (i.e. trendy, expensive) and old school (betting shops, pound shops). Minutes from the flat you'll find a great greengrocer, a fish and chip shop, late-opening corner shops, fab cheap Turkish restaurants, plus cafes and pubs. We've marked many of these on our tailor-made online airbnb guidebook, a printout of which you'll find in the flat. Newly uber-trendy Dalston and the more established somewhat hippy chick/ yummy mummy Stoke Newington are within walking distance, as is Islington's famous Upper Street, and getting to central London is easy by bus or tube.
notes: Please fill in your profile and post a photo before submitting a reservation or making an enquiry. No third party bookings please - if you're booking you need to be the person staying here, it's an AIRBNB requirement. We offer flexible check in and check out but please consult us before booking travel which will mean you arrive early (before 11am) or late (after 8pm). Same applies for a late check out (after midday) though usually that's not a problem - you can leave your bags and collect them later or even stay in the flat if we aren't back until late ourselves.  Please note we allow smoking in the (very well-aired) flat so if you are sensitive to any lingering trace of cigarette smoke, you may prefer somewhere else.
transit: The nearest tube station is Canonbury (6 - 8 mins walk), on the fast and frequent London Overground. Canonbury to Camden Road (for Camden Market) is 7 mins; Hampstead Heath, a glorious huge park, is about 20 mins away; Shoreditch High Street (for Brick Lane) is 9 mins. Oxford Circus is 20 mins away, with one change at Highbury & Islington. The Olympic Park and Westfield - a huge shopping mall at Stratford - are 15 minutes away, again on the Overground. South Kensington Tube Station - for the V & A, Natural History Museum, Science Museum and Hyde Park - is approx 30 mins by Overground and tube. Local buses serve the City & London Bridge, Waterloo & the South Bank, Soho, Piccadilly, Victoria and Oxford Street to name but a few. We provide tube maps, general transport info, hand-drawn maps of the local area and fold-out pocket maps of London in the AIRBNB drawer in our flat to help you find your way around easily. host_about:
Gareth is a musician and teacher, I work in publishing. We're born and bred Londoners and we voted to stay in the EU (sigh). We love lazy mornings, galleries, museums, reading, walking and eating as well as meeting new people and flying off to new places. We also love going away in our 1972 VW camper van which, despite its advanced age, has managed to get us to Sweden, Denmark, Germany, France and the Netherlands.

We have used airbnb as guests since 2009 and stayed in some great places in Berlin, Istanbul, New York, Lisbon, Rome and Barcelona among others. We've enjoyed meeting some great hosts too. We are super tidy, reliable and considerate of other people's places.

We are now hosting as we want to get away more often and it makes sense not to leave the flat empty. Since we started hosting we have welcomed guests from all over the world - Spain, Germany, Switzerland, Denmark, France, Italy, the US and Australia - as well as from all over the UK

What do we particularly love about hosting? Meeting some truly lovely people, making them feel at home, discovering how respectful people are of our flat and knowing that we have contributed to them having a great stay in London.

neighborhood_overview: Especially since the Brixton hero David Bowie died in January 2016 everyone who comes to London will have heard of Brixton as Bowie's birthplace. Brixton is a wonderful place, even though of course it is changing dramatically with the influx of more and more wealthy people, it is losing some of its multiethnic, creative and vibrant rough liveliness. Nonetheless it is still a great place to live and of course visit. The flat is at what used to be known as the 'front line' during the Brixton riots in the 1980s. Now you will not notice any of this, but if you are interested check out some historic facts about Brixton.  We also live very close to Brixton Market, where you can buy fruit and vegetable from all over the world, as well as local produce. Brixton pretty much has got everything you need for a great city break. Restaurants, night life, you name it. Lots of nice outdoor areas. Brockwell Park is less than 5 min walk away.
